HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1152
By Vital
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Booker Taliaferro Woods
of Georgetown.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Booker Taliaferro Woods of Georgetown; and
WHEREAS, Booker T. Woods was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Woods was born on October 1, 1938, to William and Mattie B. Woods;
he was raised in Georgetown and graduated from Booker T. Washington High School in 1958;
and
WHEREAS, Booker Woods built a career in the logging industry, working as an
entrepreneur for over fifty years; he established a reputation for his strong work ethic and
dedication to providing for his family and friends; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Woods found joy in his church, spending time with family, and following
sports; he will be remembered for his generosity, his willingness to help others, and the love he
shared so freely; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by his wife of sixty-four
years, Elizabeth Woods; daughter, Lisa Woods; stepson, Walter Miller; grandchildren, Latasia
(Donnell) Priest, India Miller, and Eric Miller; brothers, Chancel Woods and Howard (Estella)
Woods; brother-in-law, Scott (Sonya) Swafford; sister-in-law, Claire Swafford; special nephews,
Barry Bradford and Thomas Swafford; and a host of extended family and friends; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, Mr. Woods was preceded in death by his sisters,
Frances Spence, Beatrice Woods, Hortense Williams, Alice Crawford, Mildred Bradford, Loyce
HJR1152
015427
- 1 -

Whaley, and Alma Rose Woods; brothers, Harold Woods, Leonard Woods, Quentin Woods,
William Woods, Leander Woods, Ray Woods, Roy Woods, and Roland Woods; and
WHEREAS, Booker Woods leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should remember the
bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Booker Taliaferro Woods, reflecting fondly upon
his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage
and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Woods.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
